Here's how to save/restore draft text using Window lifecycle events:

**In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` with a custom Window subclass:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new MainPage());
}
```

**Create `AppWindow.cs`:**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        SaveDraft(); // Android back-button can skip Stopped
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is MainPage mainPage)
            mainPage.RestoreDraft();
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Page is MainPage mainPage)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", mainPage.GetDraftText());
    }
}
```

**In your note-taking page:**

```csharp
public partial class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        // Restore on first launch too
        RestoreDraft();
    }

    public string GetDraftText() => DraftEditor.Text ?? string.Empty;

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        DraftEditor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped`.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **Keep handlers fast** (<1–2 seconds) to avoid ANR/watchdog kills.
- `Preferences` is ideal for small text. For large documents, use file I/O instead.
